Understanding max_tokens

Think of tokens as "word pieces" - about 1 token = ¾ of a word.
What It Controls:

    Response length limit

    Cost/usage (more tokens = more cost)

    Prevents super long responses

Visual Examples:

Example 1: max_tokens=50 (Very short)
python

response = client.chat.completions.create(
    model="deepseek-chat",
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": "Tell me about climate change"}],
    max_tokens=50  # About 40 words
)
# AI might return: "Climate change refers to long-term shifts in temperatures..."
# Stops around 50 tokens

Example 2: max_tokens=200 (Medium response)
python

response = client.chat.completions.create(
    model="deepseek-chat",
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": "Explain how solar panels work"}],
    max_tokens=200  # About 150 words
)
# Returns a paragraph explanation

Example 3: max_tokens=1000 (Long response)
python

response = client.chat.completions.create(
    model="deepseek-chat",
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": "Write a detailed guide on starting a vegetable garden"}],
    max_tokens=1000  # About 750 words
)
# Returns a comprehensive guide with multiple sections

